In this article, Lawrence H. Summers, who was a key economic advisor to President Obama, discusses the progress made in rescuing and rebuilding the US economy. He highlights the dire state of the economy at the start of the year, with fear and lack of confidence being widespread. President Obama's approach was to prioritize restoring confidence and breaking the cycle of economic contraction and financial failure. He emphasized the need for productive investment and long-term growth rather than relying on asset bubbles. Summers acknowledges the substantial progress made in rescuing the economy from the risk of collapse, but also emphasizes the need for a rebuilt American economy that is more export-oriented, environmentally oriented, and less focused on financial engineering. He also emphasizes the importance of a middle-class-oriented economy that benefits a larger share of the population. Overall, Summers presents an ambitious agenda that aims to lay a foundation for future prosperity and build confidence in the current recovery.